Strategy Design Pattern in C# (A to Z) – Interview + Real Project Explanation

1. Why Strategy Pattern Came Into Picture?

Imagine you are building a Buy & Sell Property Application.

A customer can pay using:

Credit Card

UPI

Net Banking

Wallet


Without Strategy Pattern:

public class PaymentService
{
    public void ProcessPayment(string paymentType)
    {
        if(paymentType == "CreditCard")
        {
            Console.WriteLine("Processing Credit Card Payment");
        }
        else if(paymentType == "UPI")
        {
            Console.WriteLine("Processing UPI Payment");
        }
        else if(paymentType == "Wallet")
        {
            Console.WriteLine("Processing Wallet Payment");
        }
    }
}

Problem

Suppose tomorrow business says:

Add PayPal

Add Crypto

Add EMI


You must modify the existing class again and again.

This violates the Open/Closed Principle:

> Software should be open for extension but closed for modification.




---

2. What is Strategy Pattern?

Easy Definition

Strategy Pattern allows us to put different algorithms (behaviors) into separate classes and choose one at runtime.

Interview Definition

Strategy Design Pattern defines a family of algorithms, encapsulates each one, and makes them interchangeable at runtime.


---

Real Life Example

Think about Google Maps.

You want to go from Bangalore to Mysore.

Google Maps gives options:

Car

Bike

Walking

Bus


Destination is same.

Only route calculation strategy changes.

Source -------> Destination

Car Strategy
Bike Strategy
Walking Strategy
Bus Strategy

Google Maps selects strategy dynamically.

This is Strategy Pattern.


---

3. Structure of Strategy Pattern

Three main components:

1. Strategy Interface

Common contract.

IPaymentStrategy


---

2. Concrete Strategies

Actual implementations.

CreditCardPayment
UPIPayment
WalletPayment


---

3. Context

Uses selected strategy.

PaymentService


---

Diagram

IPaymentStrategy
                   |
     -----------------------------
     |             |             |
CreditCard      UPI         Wallet
Strategy      Strategy     Strategy

                   ^
                   |
             PaymentService


---

4. Step-by-Step Coding

Step 1: Create Strategy Interface

public interface IPaymentStrategy
{
    void Pay(decimal amount);
}

This is the contract.

Every payment method must implement Pay().


---

Step 2: Credit Card Strategy

public class CreditCardPayment : IPaymentStrategy
{
    public void Pay(decimal amount)
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"Paid {amount} using Credit Card");
    }
}


---

Step 3: UPI Strategy

public class UPIPayment : IPaymentStrategy
{
    public void Pay(decimal amount)
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"Paid {amount} using UPI");
    }
}


---

Step 4: Wallet Strategy

public class WalletPayment : IPaymentStrategy
{
    public void Pay(decimal amount)
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"Paid {amount} using Wallet");
    }
}


---

Step 5: Context Class

public class PaymentService
{
    private readonly IPaymentStrategy _paymentStrategy;

    public PaymentService(IPaymentStrategy paymentStrategy)
    {
        _paymentStrategy = paymentStrategy;
    }

    public void MakePayment(decimal amount)
    {
        _paymentStrategy.Pay(amount);
    }
}

Context doesn't know:

Credit Card logic

UPI logic

Wallet logic


It only knows:

Pay()

This is called Loose Coupling.


---

5. Client Code

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        IPaymentStrategy strategy =
                new UPIPayment();

        PaymentService paymentService =
                new PaymentService(strategy);

        paymentService.MakePayment(5000);
    }
}

Output:

Paid 5000 using UPI


---

Runtime Switching

IPaymentStrategy strategy =
        new CreditCardPayment();

Output:

Paid 5000 using Credit Card

No code changes inside PaymentService.

Only strategy changes.


---

6. How Execution Happens Internally

Step 1

new UPIPayment();

Object created.


---

Step 2

new PaymentService(strategy);

Strategy injected.


---

Step 3

paymentService.MakePayment(5000);

Called.


---

Step 4

_paymentStrategy.Pay(5000);

Executed.

Since actual object is UPIPayment:

UPIPayment.Pay()

runs.

This is Runtime Polymorphism.


---

