13. Interview Answer (2-Minute Version)

What is Strategy Pattern?

> Strategy Pattern is a behavioral design pattern that defines a family of algorithms, encapsulates each algorithm in a separate class, and allows them to be interchangeable at runtime. It helps remove large if-else or switch statements and follows the Open/Closed Principle.



Example:

> In a property-buying application, users can pay using Credit Card, UPI, or Wallet. Each payment method is implemented as a separate strategy class implementing a common IPaymentStrategy interface. The PaymentService uses the selected strategy at runtime without knowing the actual implementation.




---

Easy Memory Formula

Strategy Pattern =

1. Interface
      ↓
2. Multiple Implementations
      ↓
3. Context Uses Interface
      ↓
4. Select Behavior At Runtime

Think:

Google Maps

Destination = Same

Car Strategy
Bike Strategy
Walking Strategy

Only algorithm changes.

That is the Strategy Design Pattern.


//////////////////////////////////what is the runtime  polymorphism 

Great follow-up question. Runtime Polymorphism is actually one of the main reasons why the Strategy Pattern works.

What is Runtime Polymorphism?

Easy Definition

> Runtime Polymorphism means the method that will execute is decided while the program is running, not while it is being compiled.



Think:

One Interface
      ↓
Many Implementations
      ↓
Actual Method Chosen At Runtime


---

Real Life Example

Suppose you have a TV remote.

Remote → Power Button

You press the same button.

But depending on what device the remote is connected to:

TV turns ON

AC turns ON

Projector turns ON


Same button.

Different behavior.

Chosen at runtime.

This is Runtime Polymorphism.


---

C# Example

Parent Interface

public interface IAnimal
{
    void MakeSound();
}


---

Dog Class

public class Dog : IAnimal
{
    public void MakeSound()
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Dog says Woof");
    }
}


---

Cat Class

public class Cat : IAnimal
{
    public void MakeSound()
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Cat says Meow");
    }
}


---

Client Code

IAnimal animal = new Dog();

animal.MakeSound();

Output:

Dog says Woof


---

Now change only this line:

IAnimal animal = new Cat();

Output:

Cat says Meow


---

Notice:

animal.MakeSound();

is exactly the same.

But different methods execute.

Why?

Because CLR checks the actual object at runtime.

animal → Dog Object

or

animal → Cat Object

and calls the correct method.

This is Runtime Polymorphism.


---

How Strategy Pattern Uses Runtime Polymorphism

Remember:

public interface IPaymentStrategy
{
    void Pay(decimal amount);
}


---

UPI Strategy

public class UPIPayment : IPaymentStrategy
{
    public void Pay(decimal amount)
    {
        Console.WriteLine("UPI Payment");
    }
}


---

Credit Card Strategy

public class CreditCardPayment : IPaymentStrategy
{
    public void Pay(decimal amount)
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Credit Card Payment");
    }
}


---

Context

public class PaymentService
{
    private readonly IPaymentStrategy _strategy;

    public PaymentService(IPaymentStrategy strategy)
    {
        _strategy = strategy;
    }

    public void MakePayment(decimal amount)
    {
        _strategy.Pay(amount);
    }
}


---

Case 1

IPaymentStrategy strategy =
       new UPIPayment();

PaymentService payment =
       new PaymentService(strategy);

payment.MakePayment(5000);

Output:

UPI Payment


---

Case 2

IPaymentStrategy strategy =
       new CreditCardPayment();

PaymentService payment =
       new PaymentService(strategy);

payment.MakePayment(5000);

Output:

Credit Card Payment


---

Notice:

_strategy.Pay(amount);

never changes.

But the method executed changes.

That's Runtime Polymorphism.


---

What Happens Internally?

Suppose:

IPaymentStrategy strategy =
       new UPIPayment();

Memory:

strategy
    |
    ↓
UPIPayment Object


---

Then:

strategy.Pay(5000);

CLR asks:

What actual object is strategy pointing to?

Answer:

UPIPayment

So CLR executes:

UPIPayment.Pay()

If tomorrow:

strategy = new CreditCardPayment();

CLR executes:

CreditCardPayment.Pay()

Decision happens at runtime.

Hence the name:

Runtime Polymorphism

Runtime = While program is running

Poly = Many

Morph = Forms

One Interface
Many Forms
Chosen At Runtime


---

Interview Answer

What is Runtime Polymorphism?

> Runtime Polymorphism is the ability of a base class or interface reference to call different implementations of the same method based on the actual object assigned at runtime. It is achieved using method overriding or interface implementation.



Example

IAnimal animal = new Dog();
animal.MakeSound();

At runtime, the CLR sees that animal points to a Dog object and calls Dog.MakeSound().


---

Easy Memory Trick

Interface Reference
        ↓
Can Point To
        ↓
Dog
Cat
Lion
Tiger
        ↓
Same Method Call
        ↓
Different Execution
        ↓
Runtime Polymorphism

This concept is one of the pillars behind Strategy Pattern, Dependency Injection, and most modern ASP.NET Core applications.



